body:
In case a enum variant is used as the name of a pattern catch-all variable (multiple times?), it should be interpreted as a warning or an error with the understanding that the user intended to match against an enum variant and not define (unreachable) code that simply assigns a variable name to whatever the original content was:

```rust
enum SleepMode {
    Sleep,
    Stop,
    Standby,
}

fn sleep(sleep_mode: SleepMode) {
    match sleep_mode {
        Sleep => {
            println!("Sleep");
        }
        Stop => {
            println!("Step");
        }
        Standby => {
            println!("Standby");
        }
    });
}
```

Knowing there's an error here, it's immediately obvious what is going on. But this valid code, and the only clue that there's something wrong is that there's a warning about incorrectly cased variables:

```
warning: variable `Sleep` should have a snake case name such as `sleep`
   --> src/main.rs:116:9
    |
116 |         Sleep => {
    |         ^^^^^
    |
    = note: #[warn(non_snake_case)] on by default

warning: variable `Stop` should have a snake case name such as `stop`
   --> src/main.rs:120:9
    |
120 |         Stop => {
    |         ^^^^

warning: variable `Standby` should have a snake case name such as `standby`
   --> src/main.rs:127:9
    |
127 |         Standby => {
    |         ^^^^^^^
```
